WEBVTT

00:06.528 --> 00:09.139
Spade: Six dead nuns.
No one's innocent.

00:09.270 --> 00:10.880
Have you seen Teresa?

00:13.056 --> 00:16.929
♪

00:17.104 --> 00:18.801
Did you do this?

00:18.975 --> 00:21.717
How could I?
We're not allowed up here.

00:21.934 --> 00:23.849
♪

00:24.024 --> 00:27.070
She didn't want me to hate you
for what you did to my father.

00:28.289 --> 00:29.377
Get down.

00:30.900 --> 00:32.380
Man: Who is this kid

00:32.554 --> 00:34.773
that someone would kill
six people to find him?

00:37.080 --> 00:39.648
[Jazz music]

01:02.714 --> 01:05.065
I worked
for Gabrielle LaVarone.

01:05.108 --> 01:07.937
Oh. As what?
As a gardener?

01:07.980 --> 01:09.678
More like her housekeeper.

01:09.721 --> 01:11.462
Tell me your name again.

01:11.506 --> 01:12.898
Samuel Spade.

01:12.942 --> 01:14.248
Ah.

01:15.379 --> 01:16.598
How ridiculous.

01:16.640 --> 01:17.990
My mother liked it.

01:18.469 --> 01:20.384
A whore, no doubt.

01:20.428 --> 01:22.125
Maybe we'll leave
my mother out of this

01:22.169 --> 01:24.127
and focus on you and me.

01:24.649 --> 01:25.868
Yes.

01:25.911 --> 01:27.521
You and me
and this kid, then,

01:27.565 --> 01:28.783
the one that's
supposedly mine.

01:28.827 --> 01:30.176
This has nothing
to do with her.

01:30.220 --> 01:34.094
Okay.
So, do tell me,

01:34.137 --> 01:36.313
what keeps you on Le Trou?

01:36.357 --> 01:38.271
-Le what?
-Le Trou.

01:38.315 --> 01:40.709
The hole, this place.
You stay here long enough,

01:40.752 --> 01:42.363
you'll see how
inevitable the name is.

01:42.406 --> 01:45.104
I can see that just by
looking out of the window.

01:45.148 --> 01:46.497
Mm.

01:46.541 --> 01:48.847
But you don't see everything.

01:48.890 --> 01:50.283
Meaning?

01:50.327 --> 01:53.069
Sometimes,
when the sun is just so...

01:53.113 --> 01:55.463
you stand at the top
and you look down

01:55.506 --> 01:58.683
and the river and the houses
are all gone, disappeared.

01:59.684 --> 02:02.470
One day when I was a child,
the darkness was so thick

02:02.513 --> 02:05.386
that I rode with my boat
right over to La Cascade.

02:07.301 --> 02:08.693
I miss that boat.

02:08.737 --> 02:11.218
I would row
in the river every day.

02:11.261 --> 02:12.654
You understand
what I'm saying?

02:12.697 --> 02:14.612
Not really, but then
I was too busy wondering

02:14.656 --> 02:16.353
what day you might
finish talking to listen.

02:16.397 --> 02:18.573
Mm. I speak in metaphor.

02:18.616 --> 02:21.228
So all that yap about
shadows and waterfalls

02:21.271 --> 02:23.795
is really about
your unhappy childhood.

02:23.839 --> 02:25.145
Ah...

02:25.188 --> 02:27.495
You Americans
understand nothing.

02:27.538 --> 02:30.846
Fuck a Frenchwoman
in a French bed and...

02:30.889 --> 02:33.153
you'll learn
all you need to know.

02:34.241 --> 02:38.375
I don't think you and I are
having the same conversation.

02:38.984 --> 02:41.248
Of course we are.

02:41.291 --> 02:42.901
Then you're either
really dumb

02:42.945 --> 02:44.207
or you're trying
to provoke me,

02:44.251 --> 02:45.687
which also
makes you really dumb.

02:45.730 --> 02:48.559
Or you're just
what everybody says you are.

02:48.603 --> 02:51.867
Handsome?
Devil-may-care?

02:51.910 --> 02:54.348
Whatever you are and whatever
you want me to think you are,

02:54.391 --> 02:55.784
you're not drunk,
you're not bored,

02:55.827 --> 02:57.264
and you're
not at all interesting.

02:57.307 --> 02:59.091
So you can knock off
the bug act

02:59.135 --> 03:00.789
and listen
to what I have to say.

03:00.832 --> 03:03.444
I promise to be quick so you
can get back to your sulking

03:03.487 --> 03:05.272
and I can get back
to the States,

03:05.315 --> 03:07.448
where people don't butter
their fucking fruit.

03:08.100 --> 03:10.668
[Laughs]

03:10.712 --> 03:12.888
You're just an American
private copper,

03:12.931 --> 03:15.325
which in France, gives you
about the same legal authority

03:15.369 --> 03:17.414
as a rat catcher.

03:17.458 --> 03:20.417
In my case, the two jobs
are one and the same.

03:20.461 --> 03:23.594
-[Music ends]
-[Crowd applauding]

03:24.508 --> 03:27.468
Relax,
I'm not gonna shoot you.

03:33.909 --> 03:36.694
That's 500,000 francs.

03:36.738 --> 03:38.174
[Scoffs] 500,000?

03:38.218 --> 03:41.308
-That's a lot of francs.
-A whole lot.

03:41.351 --> 03:43.091
What am I supposed
to do with it?

03:43.135 --> 03:44.441
Buy yourself a new boat

03:44.485 --> 03:47.183
and row yourself
the fuck out of here.

03:47.227 --> 03:48.445
Where would I go?

03:48.489 --> 03:50.795
I hear Norway needs
more assholes.

03:51.448 --> 03:53.189
I grew up here.

03:53.233 --> 03:54.973
I still have great
love for Bozouls.

03:55.017 --> 03:57.280
Sadly,
one that's unrequited.

03:58.325 --> 03:59.716
What about the others?

03:59.761 --> 04:01.241
The neighbors
whom I care so much about?

04:01.284 --> 04:03.808
What about 'em?

04:03.852 --> 04:05.723
Will they also
bring me envelopes?

04:05.767 --> 04:07.377
No, they will not.

04:07.421 --> 04:09.510
Consider this a gift from
everyone on your little list.

04:09.553 --> 04:12.861
This is the grand total
of what you're gonna get.

04:12.904 --> 04:15.646
And what if
I choose to stay?

04:15.690 --> 04:18.954
The bottom of that hole
is a long way down.

04:18.997 --> 04:20.869
Metaphorically speaking.

04:20.911 --> 04:22.349
I'm not a man
to be threatened.

04:22.392 --> 04:23.785
If you think
I'm threatening you,

04:23.828 --> 04:25.177
then whosever that it
was taught you English

04:25.221 --> 04:27.179
didn't know a threat
from a promise.

04:29.269 --> 04:30.705
Please... [Clears throat]

04:30.748 --> 04:33.577
convey my "No, thank you"
to Madame LaVarone

04:33.621 --> 04:35.884
and all the carrots.

04:35.927 --> 04:39.235
I've asked for what I deserve
and will accept nothing less.

04:39.279 --> 04:42.064
[Jazz music plays]

04:48.810 --> 04:51.639
Philippe...

04:51.682 --> 04:53.467
you're not the worst
I've dealt with,

04:53.510 --> 04:55.251
not by a country mile.

04:58.080 --> 05:00.952
-I just want you to know that.
-Mm.

05:00.996 --> 05:03.694
Good luck with finding
a home for the girl,

05:03.738 --> 05:07.481
Mr. Spade. [Chuckles]

05:07.524 --> 05:10.092
[Jazz music continues]

05:29.590 --> 05:32.723
[Birds chirping]

05:35.683 --> 05:38.773
[Dramatic music plays]

06:09.543 --> 06:12.067
[Muffled chattering]

06:25.515 --> 06:28.475
[Keys jangling]

06:32.609 --> 06:34.611
[Dishes clinking]

06:39.877 --> 06:43.185
-As-salamu alaykum.
-[all] Wa-Alaikum-Salaam.

06:44.882 --> 06:46.623
[Speaking Arabic]

08:22.153 --> 08:25.113
[Vehicle rumbling]

08:31.554 --> 08:33.469
[Speaking French]

09:12.377 --> 09:14.118
[Door rattles]

09:14.162 --> 09:16.468
[Knocking at door]

10:09.652 --> 10:10.958
No.

10:38.420 --> 10:40.248
[Door thuds shut]

10:49.083 --> 10:51.912
[Dramatic music]

11:01.399 --> 11:04.272
[Dramatic music]

11:15.152 --> 11:17.328
Spade: The point of
the story is

11:17.372 --> 11:19.591
he wasn't sorry
for walking out on his life.

11:19.635 --> 11:22.116
That seemed reasonable
enough to him.

11:23.073 --> 11:26.381
After all, a man's nearly
killed by a falling beam,

11:26.424 --> 11:28.165
makes him stop and think.

11:28.209 --> 11:31.560
Usually the first thing
that comes to mind is run.

11:32.430 --> 11:35.085
But years later, when I saw him
with his second wife,

11:35.129 --> 11:37.087
he couldn't see
how he'd settled back

11:37.131 --> 11:40.700
into the exact same life
he'd run away from.

11:40.743 --> 11:44.007
And I bet that's the part
of the story you like best.

11:44.051 --> 11:47.141
The man adjusted himself
to beams falling

11:47.184 --> 11:48.533
and when no more
of them fell,

11:48.577 --> 11:51.275
he adjusted himself
to them not falling.

11:51.319 --> 11:53.974
You're very smart
for someone so rich.

11:54.017 --> 11:56.150
[Laughs]

11:56.193 --> 11:58.543
I guess I'm lucky
there's so little construction

11:58.587 --> 12:00.110
in Bozouls.

12:00.154 --> 12:02.373
Because I think
what you're really telling me

12:02.417 --> 12:06.813
is that you might, without
warning, leave me at any moment.

12:06.856 --> 12:09.337
I'm telling you
it's possible.

12:11.078 --> 12:14.559
Well, we have something
in common, then.

12:14.603 --> 12:17.649
Only, I'm certain
that I'd leave you.

12:17.693 --> 12:20.914
I'm also certain
that I won't be much of a wife

12:20.957 --> 12:24.308
or be able to commit to anything
beyond the end of the day.

12:26.006 --> 12:29.836
The word forever being perhaps
the most absurd of all words.

12:29.879 --> 12:31.446
To me, at least.

12:33.056 --> 12:34.449
You're ill.

12:36.407 --> 12:37.669
You can see that?

12:37.713 --> 12:40.411
Not at all.
Philippe told me.

12:40.455 --> 12:44.720
At the airport, right before
I put him on the plane.

12:46.374 --> 12:48.028
I thought he had to be lying,

12:48.071 --> 12:50.987
because, of course,
the last thing you look is ill.

12:51.031 --> 12:53.685
That's because I'm not.

12:53.729 --> 12:56.601
At least not at the moment,
anyway.

12:56.645 --> 12:59.082
I was, not that long ago.

12:59.126 --> 13:00.736
But I beat it.

13:00.780 --> 13:02.390
Or so they like to tell you.

13:04.218 --> 13:07.134
So I might leave you one day.

13:07.177 --> 13:10.398
-You might leave me one day.
-Mm.

13:11.921 --> 13:15.403
Sounds like every love story
I've ever heard.

13:18.798 --> 13:20.974
[Chuckles]

13:21.017 --> 13:23.063
[Tender music]

13:34.901 --> 13:36.685
[Car horn honks]

13:44.824 --> 13:47.261
We got a meeting with the bishop
at four o'clock.

13:47.304 --> 13:48.566
Why?

13:48.610 --> 13:50.830
Six dead monks,
if I had to guess.

13:50.873 --> 13:52.266
Want to come along?

13:52.309 --> 13:55.225
As long as no one
asks me to confess.

13:56.531 --> 13:59.273
[Engine revving]

14:01.405 --> 14:04.060
[Car rumbling]

14:06.149 --> 14:09.500
Lovely day for a swim, eh?

14:09.544 --> 14:10.937
Ah!

14:13.026 --> 14:14.766
What do you think?

14:14.810 --> 14:18.596
-Nice frame.
-Ah. Thank you.

14:19.162 --> 14:21.382
[Speaking French]

14:24.167 --> 14:27.083
Uh, I thought I'd surprise him
and hang the painting.

14:27.127 --> 14:29.129
There is a perfect spot
in the library.

14:34.047 --> 14:36.745
Right then.
Thank you.

15:44.639 --> 15:46.119
Oui.

15:51.515 --> 15:52.821
[Helena mutters]

15:55.606 --> 15:58.044
[Motorcycle rumbling]

15:59.219 --> 16:01.308
[Rain pattering]

16:22.807 --> 16:24.200
Hey!

16:31.294 --> 16:33.035
No?

16:35.255 --> 16:37.170
-[Items clatter]
-[Exclaims]

17:15.338 --> 17:16.644
Oui.

17:26.045 --> 17:29.222
[Groans, chuckles]

18:17.487 --> 18:19.533
[Bell tolls]

18:19.576 --> 18:22.013
Patrice: My confirmation name
is Sebastian.

18:23.145 --> 18:25.974
Every other boy
chose Jean or Marc.

18:26.017 --> 18:28.063
But I chose Sebastian.

18:28.672 --> 18:30.979
I said they were
Cupid's arrows.

18:31.022 --> 18:33.460
I was trying to be ironic.

18:33.503 --> 18:35.549
Not easy to do
at age 12.

18:37.290 --> 18:38.552
Maurice...

18:41.076 --> 18:42.512
[Door clicks open]

19:28.906 --> 19:30.256
Samuel Spade.

19:45.314 --> 19:48.187
-New York City.
-My condolences.

20:08.946 --> 20:10.513
The monk.
He's been found.

20:10.557 --> 20:12.950
-Where?
-Inside the Rhodes Cathedral.

20:12.994 --> 20:14.822
Doing what,
lighting a candle?

20:14.865 --> 20:17.607
Bleeding, mostly.
From a knife wound.

21:21.323 --> 21:23.325
Clement: Thank you.

21:23.369 --> 21:24.631
The boy.

21:25.893 --> 21:27.286
They want the boy.

21:27.329 --> 21:28.765
To which boy do you refer,
Mr. Spade?

21:28.809 --> 21:31.420
The Church wants him.
They want him so bad

21:31.464 --> 21:33.988
they'll overlook a few dead nuns
to get him.

21:34.031 --> 21:36.425
Oh, Mr. Spade, now even you
can understand

21:36.469 --> 21:39.167
that there's matters of Church
and there's matters of State.

21:39.210 --> 21:41.952
A distinction the Church makes
only when it suits them.

21:41.996 --> 21:44.215
I'll do my best
and I'll take that as an insult.

21:44.259 --> 21:46.566
For some,
the truth is an insult.

21:46.609 --> 21:49.220
[Chuckles] You just seem
unable to help yourself.

21:49.264 --> 21:50.657
You can wait
as long as you want

21:50.700 --> 21:52.963
for your back-flogging
friend to wake up,

21:53.007 --> 21:55.488
but he's not gonna be
of much use to you.

21:55.531 --> 21:56.924
He already lost the kid

21:56.967 --> 21:58.447
before he took
a blade to his kidney.

21:58.491 --> 22:00.928
Mr. Spade, do you have
any specific information

22:00.971 --> 22:03.017
you want to share?
-I just did.

22:11.460 --> 22:13.027
Let's go.

22:22.036 --> 22:24.604
Spade: Well, you kept
your cool, Patrice.

22:24.647 --> 22:25.909
Please.

22:25.953 --> 22:27.433
You may have not
raised your voice,

22:27.476 --> 22:29.304
but you still poked him
as hard as I did.

22:29.348 --> 22:32.351
I just like to shake the tree
to see what falls out.

22:32.394 --> 22:34.744
Except, my reckless
American friend,

22:34.788 --> 22:38.400
shake a Roman tree and you get
a face full of bird shit.

22:38.444 --> 22:40.707
[Door creaks]

22:40.750 --> 22:42.709
[Door bangs shut]

22:42.752 --> 22:45.364
Mr. Spade, Commandant.

22:45.407 --> 22:48.367
The monk's name
is Friar Angelo.

22:48.410 --> 22:51.326
I believe that he was
sent to Bozouls by

22:51.370 --> 22:54.198
Agnes Omnipotence,
it's some secret society --

22:54.242 --> 22:56.679
Wait, there's a secret society
inside the Vatican?

22:56.723 --> 22:58.202
-Yeah.
-Shocking.

22:58.246 --> 22:59.552
[Laughs] Yeah.
Who knew, right?

22:59.595 --> 23:01.031
That's why
they sent me here to help

23:01.075 --> 23:02.729
ferret out all the fanatics.

23:02.772 --> 23:05.079
As you can imagine, it hasn't
been going very easy for me.

23:05.122 --> 23:07.473
Like finding a needle
in a needle stack.

23:07.516 --> 23:09.126
Look, I don't blame you
for not trusting me.

23:09.170 --> 23:10.519
I really don't.

23:10.563 --> 23:14.044
But you and me,
we're on the same side.

23:14.088 --> 23:15.568
If you follow.

23:18.745 --> 23:20.137
[Door opens]

23:21.574 --> 23:24.446
[Door bangs shut]Okay.

23:24.490 --> 23:26.448
So we can now add the Americans

23:26.492 --> 23:29.625
to the list of people
that were chasing the kid.

23:29.669 --> 23:34.630
[ "Je me donne à qui me plaît"
by Brigitte Bardot plays]

23:51.038 --> 23:53.170
[Music continues]

24:17.760 --> 24:21.198
[Teresa sings along]

24:38.955 --> 24:40.914
A little loud,
don't you think?

24:40.957 --> 24:45.135
[Music continues]

24:45.179 --> 24:47.007
[Switch clicks, music stops]

24:47.050 --> 24:48.225
What are you doing?

24:48.269 --> 24:50.010
I need something to wear,

24:50.053 --> 24:52.447
so I thought I'd see if any
of Gabrielle's things would fit.

24:52.491 --> 24:54.231
[Birds and cicadas chirping]

24:54.275 --> 24:56.146
This was your room before.

24:56.190 --> 24:58.061
Our room, yes.

24:58.105 --> 24:59.933
Why don't you sleep
in here anymore?

24:59.976 --> 25:02.544
I never liked the view.
I prefer to see the sunset.

25:02.588 --> 25:04.111
Did you buy her this dress?

25:04.154 --> 25:06.809
Gabrielle didn't need me
for things like that.

25:06.853 --> 25:08.376
Ah, she had exquisite taste.

25:08.419 --> 25:10.421
In everything but men.

25:12.641 --> 25:14.121
How come there
are no photographs

25:14.164 --> 25:15.818
of Gabrielle's
first husband?

25:15.862 --> 25:18.299
The marriage ended badly.

25:18.952 --> 25:21.215
-Did he beat her?
-Her, no.

25:21.258 --> 25:23.783
Okay, let's play a game,
you and I.

25:23.826 --> 25:27.090
It's called,
"I won't lie to Sam."

25:27.134 --> 25:28.527
Doesn't sound like
much fun.

25:28.570 --> 25:30.833
And the rules are
I ask you a question

25:30.877 --> 25:33.401
and you answer without lying,
if that's even possible.

25:33.444 --> 25:35.229
How does one win this game?

25:35.272 --> 25:37.971
Well, that's the thing, you
can't win, you can only lose.

25:38.014 --> 25:40.147
What do I lose?Your self-respect.

25:40.190 --> 25:41.670
Question number one.

25:41.714 --> 25:44.107
Did Philippe tell you
where the boy came from?

25:44.151 --> 25:46.066
Algeria.

25:46.109 --> 25:48.808
-Anything more specific, a town?
-No.

25:50.374 --> 25:53.421
Papa said the boy was rich,
or his family was.

25:53.464 --> 25:56.119
-See how easy this is?
-You're not a nice person.

25:56.163 --> 25:57.904
I like to think
I grow on people.

25:57.947 --> 26:00.384
Question number two.
Did he mention a family name?

26:00.428 --> 26:01.995
No.

26:02.038 --> 26:04.475
Question three. Did this rich
family hire Philippe

26:04.519 --> 26:06.260
to bring the kid
over to France?

26:06.303 --> 26:08.218
Not sure about that one.

26:08.784 --> 26:11.570
Papa said he was being paid
to take care of him.

26:11.613 --> 26:14.007
What, they hated
the boy that much?

26:14.050 --> 26:15.312
What?

26:15.356 --> 26:18.228
Never mind.
Question number four.

26:18.272 --> 26:20.187
After leaving the boy
at the convent,

26:20.230 --> 26:22.972
did Philippe tell you
where he was going next?

26:23.016 --> 26:25.105
-You already asked me that one.
-You already lied.

26:25.148 --> 26:27.063
This is your shot
at redemption.

26:27.107 --> 26:28.369
I wasn't lying.

26:28.412 --> 26:30.284
I don't know where he went.

26:30.327 --> 26:33.635
[Birds chirping,
dog barking]

26:34.984 --> 26:36.899
He was coming back.

26:36.943 --> 26:39.293
And you know this how?

26:39.336 --> 26:42.949
Stop the fashion show
and answer me.

26:52.088 --> 26:53.655
I know that he's close by.

26:53.699 --> 26:55.918
Why, because
you're so important to him?

26:55.962 --> 26:58.573
No, because Zaid is.

27:01.837 --> 27:03.883
[Speaking Arabic]

28:18.740 --> 28:21.264
[Paper rustles]

28:21.308 --> 28:23.397
[Pencil scratches]

28:40.066 --> 28:42.329
[Pencil scratches]

28:55.298 --> 28:58.606
[Brakes screech]

29:08.572 --> 29:11.184
[Residents talking indistinctly]

29:11.227 --> 29:13.664
[Gentle piano music]

29:19.279 --> 29:20.671
[Sings in French]

29:20.715 --> 29:22.848
[Ashtray smashes]

29:22.891 --> 29:26.765
[Speaking French]

29:26.808 --> 29:28.679
[Gentle piano music continues]

29:28.723 --> 29:30.725
[Broken ashtray clatters]

29:32.161 --> 29:34.685
[Footsteps approaching]

30:25.693 --> 30:29.436
[Singing in French]

30:36.008 --> 30:37.923
[Sam coughs]

30:41.796 --> 30:44.538
Take off
your jacket and sit down.

30:47.584 --> 30:50.022
-Oh, right.
-Katrine.

30:54.243 --> 30:55.984
I need a favor.

30:56.028 --> 30:59.161
Which I will listen to right
after I listen to your chest.

30:59.945 --> 31:04.819
Audrey Saint-Andre is
a patient of yours, is she not?

31:04.863 --> 31:06.734
Sit down.

31:14.263 --> 31:16.091
Cough.

31:16.135 --> 31:20.052
[Coughs] Is she...
[Coughs]

31:23.751 --> 31:26.493
Did we not agree
that the smoking would stop?

31:26.536 --> 31:30.671
Agree?
No, you insisted, I equivocated,

31:30.714 --> 31:32.716
told you
what you wanted to hear.

31:32.760 --> 31:35.458
I'm telling you,
quit or die.

31:35.502 --> 31:38.940
There's that adorable tenderness
you French are so famous for.

31:38.984 --> 31:40.811
You prefer
I beat around the bush?

31:40.855 --> 31:43.989
When me dying
is on the table, yes.

31:44.032 --> 31:45.773
[Telephone rings]

31:45.816 --> 31:49.342
You've never struck me as
a man who yields to temptation.

31:49.385 --> 31:51.257
Where is your famous
willpower?

31:51.300 --> 31:52.954
I try to quit.

31:52.998 --> 31:55.217
I just keep finding cigarettes
between my fingers.

31:55.261 --> 31:56.610
Try harder.

31:56.653 --> 31:58.438
I'm gonna have
those words painted

31:58.481 --> 32:00.048
on the ceiling of my bedroom.

32:00.092 --> 32:02.224
Is Audrey a patient?

32:02.268 --> 32:04.400
Everyone in this town is,

32:04.444 --> 32:06.533
from birth to burial,

32:06.576 --> 32:10.624
though in Audrey's case,
she was also my nurse

32:10.667 --> 32:12.278
and quite a good one.

32:12.321 --> 32:14.367
I'm sure she
and her shotgun

32:14.410 --> 32:16.847
had a terrific
bedside manner.

32:16.891 --> 32:19.328
Why are you curious
about Audrey?

32:19.372 --> 32:21.852
Is she due
for an exam anytime soon?

32:21.896 --> 32:23.419
No.

32:23.463 --> 32:26.248
Can you come up with a reason
why you have to see her?

32:26.292 --> 32:27.554
Why would I?

32:27.597 --> 32:29.556
I need to find Philippe.

32:29.599 --> 32:31.775
Knowing that jackal,

32:31.819 --> 32:34.735
he has long since crept
into the underbrush.

32:34.778 --> 32:37.129
Maybe,
but if he were to hear

32:37.172 --> 32:39.305
that something
had happened to Teresa,

32:39.348 --> 32:41.176
he might show himself.

32:41.220 --> 32:42.743
Like what sort
of something?

32:42.786 --> 32:44.571
Like her being shot.

32:48.792 --> 32:50.272
You want me to lie
to his mother

32:50.316 --> 32:52.318
to say that Teresa was hurt?

32:52.361 --> 32:54.146
Not hurt, shot.

32:54.189 --> 32:55.625
Hurt can mean anything

32:55.669 --> 32:58.193
between stubbed her toe
and fell out of bed.

32:58.237 --> 32:59.803
Shot can only mean shot.

32:59.847 --> 33:02.458
You presume Audrey
cares about the girl.

33:02.502 --> 33:04.112
I presume she speaks
to her son.

33:04.156 --> 33:06.854
And you presume
he cares about the girl.

33:06.897 --> 33:08.943
His reasons might not be
the most paternal,

33:08.987 --> 33:12.860
but Philippe has a real interest
in keeping her healthy.

33:16.385 --> 33:18.474
I will go to Audrey

33:18.518 --> 33:21.912
and check her blood pressure,
which is very high.

33:22.652 --> 33:24.176
And while I'm there,

33:24.219 --> 33:27.701
perhaps the subject
of the girl will come up.

33:27.744 --> 33:30.356
Be sure to subtly drop
into the conversation

33:30.399 --> 33:32.445
that she's staying
at my house.

33:32.488 --> 33:34.142
I am always subtle.

33:34.186 --> 33:36.231
Like a ball-peen hammer.

33:36.275 --> 33:38.451
Sometimes what's best
is to keep the bodies buried.

33:38.494 --> 33:43.543
Often death is the best cure,
often a relief.

33:43.586 --> 33:47.286
They teach you that bit of
"deepitude" in medical school?

33:49.027 --> 33:50.289
Buchenwald.

33:56.643 --> 33:58.993
[Customers talking indistinctly]

34:02.040 --> 34:03.302
Monsieur Spade...

34:09.264 --> 34:10.483
Oui.

34:21.146 --> 34:24.366
[Car revs]

34:24.409 --> 34:26.976
[Customers talking indistinctly]

34:28.196 --> 34:30.632
Do you mind?I'm speaking to a lawyer.

34:30.677 --> 34:32.025
Seriously, Jean-Pierre,

34:32.070 --> 34:34.159
I prefer to be harassed
on a full stomach.

34:34.202 --> 34:37.335
Gabrielle trusted me.
She believed in me.

34:37.379 --> 34:39.206
That was before
you stole from her.

34:39.251 --> 34:42.254
That is only a sliver
of the whole truth.

34:45.561 --> 34:46.780
[Plate scrapes]

34:46.822 --> 34:48.172
Try me.

34:48.216 --> 34:50.262
When I was 16,
I was in love with her.

34:50.304 --> 34:52.438
A ridiculous thing to say,
but I was.

34:52.481 --> 34:53.699
Not ridiculous at all.

34:53.743 --> 34:55.440
Not when we're talking
about Gabrielle.

34:55.484 --> 34:56.703
But she was your aunt.

34:56.746 --> 34:59.401
Not by blood.
I called her aunt,

34:59.445 --> 35:01.490
but Gabrielle and my mother
were close friends.

35:01.534 --> 35:02.796
Only friends.

35:02.839 --> 35:05.146
-She never told you this?
-No.

35:05.190 --> 35:08.280
So, she never told you
that they met at Charenton?

35:08.323 --> 35:11.152
The hospital? [Coughs]

35:11.196 --> 35:13.894
The asylum,
where my mother was a cook

35:13.937 --> 35:16.331
after she divorced
my father.

35:16.375 --> 35:17.854
Why was Gabrielle there?

35:17.898 --> 35:20.379
She was admitted
right after Jacques died.

35:22.468 --> 35:23.947
You really didn't know this?

35:23.991 --> 35:27.212
No, we never really
talked about Jacques,

35:27.255 --> 35:28.735
apart from the fact
that he was dead

35:28.778 --> 35:30.563
and how he got that way.

35:30.606 --> 35:32.782
She wasn't the same
afterwards.

35:32.826 --> 35:34.132
And now you're gonna tell me

35:34.175 --> 35:35.611
you don't think
she was in her right mind

35:35.655 --> 35:37.396
when she made her will.

35:37.439 --> 35:39.267
The possibility,
my lawyer says.

35:39.311 --> 35:42.444
Which is legalese
for "tough to prove,"

35:42.488 --> 35:43.880
especially since
Jacques died

35:43.924 --> 35:46.231
eight years
before I even got here.

35:48.189 --> 35:50.409
[Plates and cutlery clattering]

35:58.112 --> 35:59.940
I was on leave,

35:59.983 --> 36:03.117
glad to be back in Bozouls,
excited to see Gabrielle,

36:03.161 --> 36:06.599
but there you were,
living in her house.

36:06.642 --> 36:08.209
She wasn't
the same with me.

36:08.253 --> 36:10.777
Bullshit.
I don't buy that you came home

36:10.820 --> 36:13.214
and got so jealous of me
that you stole from her.

36:13.258 --> 36:16.348
I needed the money
to get myself out of the army.

36:16.391 --> 36:19.089
I was desperate not wanting
to go back and fight.

36:19.133 --> 36:21.309
Philippe knew a colonel

36:21.353 --> 36:23.790
who, for a price,
could get me discharged.

36:23.833 --> 36:26.096
That sounds like Philippe,

36:26.140 --> 36:29.274
helping out a childhood pal
for a price.

36:29.317 --> 36:31.493
But you didn't have
to steal from Gabrielle.

36:31.537 --> 36:33.365
She would've given you
whatever you needed.

36:33.408 --> 36:36.498
She also would've forgiven me
for my mistake,

36:36.542 --> 36:38.500
one I have paid for.

36:38.544 --> 36:40.502
Then don't make another one.

36:40.546 --> 36:41.895
You have a wife at home

36:41.938 --> 36:44.332
who is trying
to find a way back to you.

36:44.376 --> 36:45.594
That's something.

36:45.638 --> 36:48.771
No, Marguerite
has moved on.

36:48.815 --> 36:51.165
She doesn't want to admit that,
she doesn't want to hurt me,

36:51.209 --> 36:53.950
but she doesn't feel
the same as I do.

36:53.994 --> 36:56.388
So, I must go away.

36:56.431 --> 37:00.130
But not before I can make sure
my wife is taken care of by me.

37:00.174 --> 37:02.132
So, this is all
just for her?

37:02.176 --> 37:03.917
For both of us.

37:03.960 --> 37:05.266
You must be drunk
if you think

37:05.310 --> 37:07.834
I'm just gonna hand over
the vineyard to you.

37:07.877 --> 37:10.489
Ha, that's not
the kind of man you are.

37:10.532 --> 37:13.056
In fact, when I first saw
Gabrielle in your arms,

37:13.100 --> 37:16.364
I thought someone like you --Someone like me, what?

37:16.408 --> 37:19.280
Couldn't really love
someone like Gabrielle?

37:19.324 --> 37:21.195
The other way around.

37:21.239 --> 37:24.329
Look, Spade, I just want
to know my rights and --

37:24.372 --> 37:25.939
You don't have any.

37:25.982 --> 37:28.115
If I have none,
I will accept that I have lost.

37:28.158 --> 37:29.421
I will leave Bozouls.

37:29.464 --> 37:31.336
But at least
I will know what is true

37:31.379 --> 37:33.163
instead of simply
accepting your version.

37:33.990 --> 37:37.255
And if you do have
a legitimate claim?

37:37.298 --> 37:40.693
I will ask
that you give me a fair price

37:40.736 --> 37:42.216
and I will still leave.

37:42.260 --> 37:44.131
[Coughing]

37:46.655 --> 37:50.050
[Dog barks]

37:50.093 --> 37:52.270
I'm not gonna
fight you anymore.

37:52.313 --> 37:55.316
If I want you dead,
I just have to wait.

37:55.925 --> 37:59.799
And, from what I can see,
the wait won't be long.

38:01.322 --> 38:02.628
[Plate scrapes]

38:02.671 --> 38:05.326
Bon appétit.

38:05.370 --> 38:06.936
[Customers talking indistinctly]

38:06.980 --> 38:09.069
[Church bell tolls]

38:09.112 --> 38:13.465
[ "La Valse A Mille Temps"
by Jacques Brel plays
on phonograph]

38:13.508 --> 38:15.510
[Music continues]

38:17.425 --> 38:19.253
[Knocking on door]

38:29.394 --> 38:31.091
Simon?

38:36.618 --> 38:40.579
[Music continues]

38:51.633 --> 38:53.287
[Knocking on door]

38:55.507 --> 38:58.248
[Bottles clinking]

39:08.128 --> 39:09.608
No.
Mm-hmm.

39:29.497 --> 39:32.413
[Music continues]

39:32.457 --> 39:34.981
[Switch clicks,
music stops]

39:37.070 --> 39:38.767
[Birds chirping]

40:03.531 --> 40:05.925
[Footsteps approaching]

40:10.059 --> 40:12.018
I remember meeting you.

40:13.367 --> 40:16.326
We were in a room
that was very hot.

40:16.370 --> 40:17.937
I was dizzy
and could barely breathe

40:17.980 --> 40:19.939
but you wouldn't look at me.

40:19.982 --> 40:21.331
After that, all of a sudden,

40:21.375 --> 40:22.985
I was on an airplane next
to you.

40:23.029 --> 40:25.684
Istanbul is pretty hot
that time of year.

40:26.989 --> 40:28.338
What was I doing there?

40:28.382 --> 40:30.340
Only your mother
can fill you in on that.

40:30.384 --> 40:32.691
All I was told
is where to find you.

40:34.127 --> 40:36.085
The money in my trust fund,

40:36.129 --> 40:37.696
how did she have so much?

40:38.566 --> 40:41.351
Your mother had
a nose for antiques.

40:41.395 --> 40:42.962
My father?

40:43.005 --> 40:46.400
He had a nose
for people's weaknesses.

40:46.444 --> 40:49.229
-He stole the antiques?
-And worse.

40:51.187 --> 40:52.580
I hope he never comes back.

40:52.624 --> 40:54.713
Well, that's
a swerve in attitude.

40:55.801 --> 40:57.455
I wanna live here.

40:57.498 --> 40:59.935
With your own Coke and
a bottomless bottle of brandy?

40:59.979 --> 41:01.284
Who could blame you?

41:01.328 --> 41:03.286
I wanna live here with you.

41:03.330 --> 41:06.115
That's an even
bigger swerve.

41:06.159 --> 41:08.988
[Birds chirping]

41:09.031 --> 41:10.598
Atta girl.

41:10.642 --> 41:12.774
Give me your best of outlook,
don't say a word,

41:12.818 --> 41:14.733
and maybe I'll fall
for this bullshit.

41:14.776 --> 41:16.691
Why should I say anything?
You don't believe me when I do.

41:16.735 --> 41:20.042
That's because you lie the way
other people blink or inhale.

41:20.086 --> 41:21.870
It's automatic.

41:21.914 --> 41:25.134
And I'm afraid, when the convent
reopens, you're going back.

41:25.178 --> 41:27.136
-No, I won't.
-You don't have a choice.

41:27.180 --> 41:29.791
-When I'm 18, I will.
-But you're not 18.

41:29.835 --> 41:31.401
When I get that money,

41:31.445 --> 41:33.186
I'm leaving
this stupid little town.

41:33.229 --> 41:34.535
If that's what you want.

41:34.579 --> 41:36.015
Maybe I'll go back
to San Francisco

41:36.058 --> 41:37.669
and find out
a few of your secrets.

41:42.195 --> 41:45.111
[Telephone ringing]

41:59.604 --> 42:01.170
Hello?

42:01.214 --> 42:03.608
Philippe: Somebody took
a shot at Teresa?

42:03.651 --> 42:05.218
Philippe?

42:05.261 --> 42:07.176
I had
nothing to do with that.

42:07.220 --> 42:10.223
No, but you pulled her
into your bullshit.

42:10.266 --> 42:12.268
Is the boy with you?

42:12.312 --> 42:14.619
You want to have
a real conversation?

42:14.662 --> 42:16.229
Knock on my door.

42:16.272 --> 42:18.144
Nine o'clock, the cemetery.

42:18.187 --> 42:20.276
The cemetery?
Are you fucking kidding?

42:20.320 --> 42:22.322
[Line disconnects,
dial tone]

42:32.071 --> 42:34.508
[Ominous orchestral music]

42:37.990 --> 42:39.513
[Door clicks]

42:44.997 --> 42:50.132
[Gentle trumpet
and orchestral music]

42:54.267 --> 42:56.922
[Gun clicks]

43:01.013 --> 43:05.539
[Trumpet and orchestral
music continues]

43:08.629 --> 43:11.197
[Footsteps thudding]

43:11.980 --> 43:13.982
[Door thuds]

43:14.026 --> 43:18.160
[ "J'suis D'accord"
by Francoise Hardy
plays on phonograph]

43:33.349 --> 43:35.961
[Car revs]

43:50.540 --> 43:52.151
[Dog barking]

43:52.194 --> 43:53.935
[Car door slams]

43:53.979 --> 43:55.807
[Cicadas chirping]

43:59.245 --> 44:02.422
[Cats squabbling]

44:19.918 --> 44:23.443
[Undergrowth rustling]

44:24.487 --> 44:27.055
[Animal barking]

44:27.099 --> 44:29.754
[Owl hooting]

44:32.017 --> 44:34.454
[Car revs]

44:40.068 --> 44:42.592
[Fox howls]

44:43.637 --> 44:46.684
[Cicadas chirping]

44:49.077 --> 44:52.211
[Motorbike revs, backfires]

45:01.220 --> 45:05.659
[Suspenseful guitar
and orchestral music]

45:15.974 --> 45:18.672
[Car revs]

45:23.329 --> 45:25.810
[Brakes squealing]

45:27.681 --> 45:30.684
[Suspenseful orchestral
music intensifies]

45:38.910 --> 45:41.260
[Snoring]

45:41.303 --> 45:43.523
[Sam panting]

45:43.566 --> 45:45.525
[Suspenseful violin music]

45:54.316 --> 45:57.363
[Door creaks]

45:59.017 --> 46:01.323
[Door closes]

46:02.237 --> 46:04.065
[Gun clicks]

46:04.109 --> 46:06.851
[Dramatic orchestral music]

46:08.069 --> 46:10.028
[Sighs]

46:15.990 --> 46:17.557
[Cork plops]

46:24.477 --> 46:26.392
You missed your chance...

46:28.611 --> 46:29.874
to shoot me.

46:35.270 --> 46:36.750
Oh...

46:36.794 --> 46:39.057
it's no Van Gogh,
but it's not that bad.

46:43.104 --> 46:44.671
Gabrielle would have.

46:51.634 --> 46:53.898
If this is about
your raise...

47:14.440 --> 47:16.181
[Sam gulps and sighs]

47:16.224 --> 47:17.660
[Glass shatters]

47:17.704 --> 47:19.575
[Loud thud]

47:19.619 --> 47:21.055
Helena?

47:21.099 --> 47:22.796
Someone's in the house.

47:30.369 --> 47:31.936
Sam: Helena?

47:32.762 --> 47:36.070
[Hand thumps, Sam grunts]

47:37.724 --> 47:39.030
[Sam grunts]

47:39.073 --> 47:40.727
[Thudding]

47:43.338 --> 47:46.820
[Sam grunting]

47:48.082 --> 47:49.475
Ah!

47:49.518 --> 47:52.565
[Objects clattering]

47:52.608 --> 47:55.829
[Choking and grunting]

47:59.050 --> 48:00.442
Ah.

48:02.270 --> 48:04.620
[Footsteps approaching]

48:08.450 --> 48:09.930
[Door opens]

48:11.149 --> 48:13.151
[Floorboards creaking]

48:14.369 --> 48:16.067
The girl.

48:16.110 --> 48:19.766
Sit.
We're not to intervene.

48:19.809 --> 48:21.420
[Sam and assailant scuffling]

48:21.463 --> 48:24.902
Teresa: [Screams] Mr. Spade!

48:27.861 --> 48:29.776
[Gun fires]

48:32.561 --> 48:42.441
♪

48:42.484 --> 48:52.407
♪

48:52.451 --> 49:02.417
♪

49:02.983 --> 49:04.419
♪♪I'm gonna ask you
some questions,

49:04.463 --> 49:05.594
and every time
you don't answer,

49:05.725 --> 49:06.769
I'm going to kick you
in the head.

49:06.944 --> 49:08.467
Sound good?
[ Grunts ]

49:09.903 --> 49:11.861
I'm so glad you could
join us for a meal.

49:12.384 --> 49:14.038
After what I saw
floating in your pool,

49:14.168 --> 49:15.604
I'm a bit twitchy.

49:15.735 --> 49:17.345
Just glad I could help.Sam: Knock it off,

49:17.432 --> 49:18.781
and tell me
what's going on.

49:21.393 --> 49:23.699
Cynthia: We all pretend,
Mr. Spade.

49:23.873 --> 49:27.007
[Gunshot]Sam: You have many enemies.

49:27.138 --> 49:29.967
Cynthia:
Did someone get lost?Apparently so.
